Cholera, imported - Guam & Europe: RFI 981114221052
Date: 7 Jul 2000 09:41:46 +0300
From: Stephen Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background data on cholera in Oceania were abstracted from
GIDEON <http://www.cyinfo.com>
American Samoa - No cases were reported during 1990 to 1999.
Australia - _Vibrio cholerae_ is occasionally identified in sewage and
natural water. No cases of _Vibrio cholerae_ O139 infection have been
reported to date. Forty-one cases of cholera were reported in 1972. From
1992 through March, 2000, 31 cases of imported cholera were reported with
numbers ranging from 1 to 5 cases per year.
Fiji - Cholera is not reported in Fiji; however, two tourists from New
Zealand developed the disease while in Fiji (1998 and 1999). _Vibrio
cholerae_ 019 (but not 01) was identified in fresh water samples in 1999.
New Zealand - Two cases (imported, nonfatal) were reported in 1994; 2
(imported, nonfatal) in 1995; 0 in 1996; 0 in 1997; 1 (imported from Fiji,
nonfatal) in 1998; 1 (imported from Fiji, nonfatal) in 1999.
Samoa - 13 cases were reported in 1979; 0 during 1990 to 1997.
Trust Territories - No cases were reported in 1978. 2214 cases were
reported in 1982; 19 in 1984; 0 during 1990 to 1995; 1 (nonfatal, in
Northern Marianas) in 1996; 3 (nonfatal, in Northern Marianas) in 1997.
The Federated States of Micronesia reported an outbreak on Pohnpei Island
in 2000 - 1596 suspected cases (9 fatal) during January to June. Two cases
were exported to Guam during the outbreak.
Tuvalu - Cholera had been reported from Nanumea and Nuitao. 293 cases (8
fatal) were reported in 1992. The area is considered cholera-free as of
January 1995.
--
Stephen Berger
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
